This rifle is built on an Arsenal of Texas (not Vegas) receiver (which is no longer around, but built top line receivers before ak's were the norm), on a Romanian G parts (thats the nice Romanian natl guard, not the crappy stuff on the market now...this is more on par with soviet parts from Russia, considering thats who built them), with Russian furniture (which, thanks to Obama, are difficult, if not next to impossible to get imported). This rifle comes with the original AK74M folding steel stock, 74 hand guards, 74 muzzle brake, original green sling, Bakelite pistol grip, Bakelite magazine, a polymer Bulgarian mag, polymer 40 rnd mag, and standard steel mag. i also am including a Arsenal (NOW we get to the las Vegas one!) correct side folding butt stock, front hand guard and pistol grip, the rails for the forend, and original ak slant brake. i also have a Texas weapons system dogleg rail top cover with rear sight, and i am throwing in at least 100 rounds of ammo. This rifle was around $2000 for custom work, and the price will steadily rise, considering certain markets. If you arent interested in this rifle, please dont email me that you can get an Arsenal of Vegas for $900 from your ffl buddy. Great, go to him, and then try to convince Arsenal to custom build you an AK to your specs on an unblemished receiver. I dont NEED to sell this rifle, Im only exploring my options. i will consider trades, especially multi AK 74s.

title: For Sale:  Forehand & Wadsworth .32 Hammerless Top-Break Revolver - Antique for Display or Restoration
postcontent:
This is a non-functioning revolver!

Forehand & Wadsworth .32 (S&W Black Powder-Only) Hammerless Top-Break Revolver

This revolver was made sometime between 1888 and 1890. The model was introduced in 1888, the company name changed sometime in 1890 to "Forehand Arms Co." after which the brand marking on the firearms changed to match. This allows for narrowing down the manufacture date to a short period. 
The matching "1926" stamping viewable on both the cylinder and bottom of the frame/handle of this revolver is the serial number, not a manufacturing date for those curious. And here again, the S/N is a fairly low number.

As-is this gun would make a nice display piece or wall hanger. It's got the surface wear to show it was a well used gun in its' day. This is a steel gun with nickel plate finnish and an after-market stained wood hand grip of unknown age and origin. All of the rusty areas of the gun are purely from the nickel having been worn off from handling over the last one hundred and twenty-five years.

Worth Noting:
- This is a non-functioning revolver!
- If in working condition, which it isn't, this would only fire gun powder based .32 cartridges. The "grain" combustible in modern ammunition creates a great deal more pressure than gun powder and could damage the revolver and cause injury to the user.
- Will entertain offers.

title: For Sale:  The Texas Ranger Dragoon
postcontent:
A museum-quality firearm for your collection that is both elegant and historically significant. Firsts are rare. The historic Texas Ranger Dragoon is the rarest of the rare.It is from the first inscribed Samuel Colt presentation revolver of which we have any record. It was presented by Samuel Colt to one of his most celebrated contemporaries, Major Ben McCulloch, a Texas Ranger whose frontier exploits during the mid-years of the 19th century have

An ardent supporter of Colt's "repeaters," McCulloch was widely regarded as one of the two most fearless men on the Texas frontier. The other was Ranger Jack Hays, another great Colt enthusiast.

With the presentation of the "McCulloch Dragoon," Samuel Colt initiated a lifelong tradition that made his name synonymous with fine firearms throughout the 19th century. He had presented firearms to illustrious contemporaries before, accompanied by letters,

This much is certain: the earliest surviving inscribed presentation Colt is Ben McCulloch's Transition Dragoon, serial number 1337. Ranger McCulloch carried his cherished Colt for the remaining 13 years of his life. During the Civil War it was with him. At the Battle of Pea Ridge, he died from a sniper's bullet. Then it mysteriously vanished

The left grip features a sterling silver medallion, 
inscribed with the Texas Ranger motto:

Free as the breeze
Swift as a mustang
Tough as a cactus

Barrel Length: 7 1/2"
Overall Length: 13 7/8"
Caliber: .44 percussion
Etchings: 24-karat gold
Backstrap: silver-plated brass
Grips: select walnut
Triggerguard: silver-plated brass
Finish: frame, hammer & loading lever, case-hardened; 
balance blued; cylinder, silver-plated.
Accessories: powder flask, bullet mold, screwdriver-nipple wrench
